    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm studying regularization for my ml class and im a bit stuck. can u explain the main difference between L1 and L2 regularization in terms of how they actually affect the model coefficients? like why would i pick one over the other?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, tends to drive some coefficients to exactly zero, effectively performing feature selection. This is useful when you believe many features are irrelevant or when you want a simpler model. L2 regularization, or Ridge, on the other hand, tends to shrink the coefficients towards zero but rarely exactly zero, which can be beneficial when you believe all features are relevant but you want to avoid overfitting. The choice between L1 and L2 often depends on the nature of your data and the problem at hand. L1 can be a good choice when you want a sparse model, while L2 is better when you want to keep all features but still control the magnitude of the coefficients.",
      "source": "target",
