    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i have a huge dataset with like 500 different variables but i suspect only a few actually matter, l1 is the way to go right? can u explain the math part of why l1 actually hits zero while l2 just gets really small? like what's happening with the optimization?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, L1 regularization is often more suitable for high-dimensional datasets where you want to identify the most significant features. Mathematically, L1 regularization adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the magnitude of the coefficients. This penalty term is added to the cost function, and during optimization, it encourages the coefficients to be as small as possible, but not necessarily zero. The optimization problem becomes:\n\nMinimize: Cost + λ * Σ|w_i|\n\nwhere Cost is the original cost function (like mean squared error), λ is the regularization parameter, and w_i are the coefficients. The L1 penalty term is the sum of the absolute values of the coefficients, multiplied by λ.\n\nL2 regularization, on the other hand, adds a penalty equal to the square of the magnitude of the coefficients. The optimization problem for L2 regularization is:\n\nMinimize: Cost + λ * Σw_i^2\n\nThe L2 penalty term is the sum of the squares of the coefficients, multiplied by λ. This penalty term encourages the coefficients to be small but doesn't necessarily drive them to zero, because the square of a small number is still small, even if negative.\n\nThe reason L1 can drive coefficients to zero is because",
      "source": "target",
