      "content": "Apologies for the cut-off! The reason L1 can drive coefficients to zero is because the absolute value function has a \"kink\" at zero. This means that the gradient of the L1 penalty term changes abruptly at zero, creating a point where the cost function has a saddle point. When you perform gradient descent, this saddle point can cause the optimization algorithm to make a sudden jump to a point where the penalty term is minimized, which can be a point where one or more coefficients are exactly zero.\n\nIn contrast, the L2 penalty term, which is the square of the coefficients, is smooth and differentiable everywhere, including at zero. This means that the gradient of the L2 penalty term is always positive, and the optimization algorithm will never encounter a saddle point that forces a coefficient to be exactly zero. Instead, it will always push the coefficients towards zero, but they will never actually reach it.\n\nThis geometric difference is why L1 regularization can result in sparse solutions (with some coefficients being exactly zero), while L2 regularization tends to produce dense solutions (with all coefficients being small but non-zero). The choice between L1 and L2 regularization can depend on the specific problem you're trying to solve and the nature of your",
